{"parse":{"title":"tea","pageid":37365,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"tea\"}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{abbrev|mul|en:'''Te'''mi'''a'''r}}.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n[[File:Cup of tea, Scotland.jpg|thumb|alt=An orange tea in a teacup|right|A cup of '''tea''' in Scotland.]]\n[[File:Names for tea.png|alt=A world map in grey with blue and red dots|thumb|Names like ''cha'' in red, names like ''tea'' in blue, and other names in grey]]\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFirst appears c. 1655, in the writings of {{w|Álvaro Semedo}}. From {{bor|en|nl|thee}}, from {{der|en|nan-hbl|茶|tr=tê}} ({{w|Amoy dialect}}), from {{der|en|och|-}}, ultimately from {{der|en|sit-pro|*s-la||leaf, tea}}. Introduced to English and other Western European languages by the {{w|Dutch East India Company}}, who sourced their tea in {{w|Amoy}}; compare {{cog|ms|teh}} along the same trade route. {{doublet|en|chai|cha}} (and, distantly, the first element of {{m|en|lahpet}}), from same Proto-Sino-Tibetan root; see discussion of cognates.\n\n{{box-top|Cognates}}\nThe word for “tea” in many languages is of Sinitic origin (due to China being the origin of the plant), and thus there are many cognates; see [[#Translations|translations]]. These are from one of two proximate sources, reflected in the phonological shape: forms with a stop (e.g. {{IPAchar|/t/}}) are derived from Min Nan ''tê'', while forms with an affricate (e.g. {{IPAchar|/tʃ/}}) are derived from other Sinitic languages, like Mandarin ''chá'' or Cantonese ''caa4'' (all written as {{zh-l|*茶}}). Different languages borrowed one or the other form (specific language and point in time varied), reflecting trade ties, generally Min Nan ''tê'' if by ocean trade from Fujian, Cantonese ''caa4'' if by ocean trade from Guangdong, or northern Chinese ''chá'' if by overland trade or by ocean trade from India.<ref>''The World Atlas of Language Structures Online,'' “[http://wals.info/feature/138 Chapter 138: Tea]”, by Östen Dahl</ref>\n\nThus Western and Northern European languages borrowed ''tê'' (with the exception of Portuguese, which uses {{m|pt|chá}}; despite being by ocean trade, their source was in {{w|Macao}}, not Amoy), while ''chá'' borrowings are used over a very large geographical area of Eurasia and Africa: Southern and Eastern Europe, and on through Turkish, Arabic, North and East Africa, Persian, Central Asian, and Indic languages. In Europe the ''tê''/''chá'' line is Italian/Slovene, Hungarian/Romanian, German/Czech, Polish/Ukrainian, Baltics/Russian, Finnish/Karelian, Northern Sami/Inari Sami. ''tê'' was also borrowed in European trade stops in Southern India and coastal Africa, though ''chá'' borrowings are otherwise more prevalent in these regions, via Arabic or Indic, due to earlier trade. The situation in Southeast Asia is complex due to multiple influences, and some languages borrowed both forms, such as Malay {{m|ms|teh}} and {{m|ms|ca}}.\n{{box-bottom}}\n\n{{senseno|en|information, especially gossip|uc=1}} (“information, especially gossip”) may be originally from ''T'' standing for {{m|en|truth}}, which evolved into ''tea''. An alternative explanation dates back to gay African-American culture in the 1970s and alludes to women gossiping over afternoon tea.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite-web |en |url=https://www.npr.org/2025/08/27/g-s1-85471/whats-tea-no-seriously-whats-tea |title=What's tea? No, seriously. What's 'tea'? |work={{w|All Things Considered}} |publisher={{w|NPR}} |date=2025-08-27 |accessdate=2025-08-28 |first=Alana |last=Wise}}</ref>\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|en|tay}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{enPR|tē|a=RP}}, {{IPA|en|/tiː/|[tʰɪj ~ tʰiː]}}\n* {{audio|en|En-uk-tea.ogg|a=RP}}\n* {{enPR|tē|a=GA}}, {{IPA|en|/ti/|[tʰi]}}\n* {{audio|en|En-us-tea.ogg|a=GA}}\n* {{audio|en|En-au-tea.ogg|a=AU}}\n* {{homophones|en|T|te|tee|ti}}\n* {{rhymes|en|iː|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|tea plant Camellia sinensis, in any subspecific variety}} {{lb|en|uncountable}} The [[tea plant]] ({{taxfmt|Camellia sinensis|species}}); {{lb|en|countable}} a [[variety]] of this [[plant]].\n#: {{ux|en|[[Darjeeling]] '''tea''' is grown in India.}}\n# {{senseid|en|leaves or buds of tea plant Camellia sinensis}} {{lb|en|uncountable}} The [[dried]] [[leaf|leaves]] or [[bud]]s of the [[tea plant]]; {{lb|en|countable}} a [[variety]] of [[such]] [[leave]]s.\n#: {{ux|en|Go to the supermarket and buy some [[Darjeeling]] '''tea'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Not for [[all the tea in China|all the '''tea''' in China]].}}\n# {{senseid|en|beverage made from tea plant Camellia sinensis}} {{lb|en|uncountable}} The [[drink]] [[made]] by [[infuse|infusing]] these [[dried]] [[leaf|leaves]] or [[bud]]s in [[hot]] [[water]].\n#: {{ux|en|Would you like some '''tea'''?}}\n#: {{ux|en| She is drinking her '''tea''' right now.}}\n#* {{RQ:Travers Cuckoo in the Nest|chapter=2|passage=Mother{{...}}considered that the exclusiveness of Peter's circle was due not to its distinction, but to the fact that it was an inner Babylon of prodigality and whoredom, from which every Kensingtonian held aloof, except on the conventional tip-and-run excursions in pursuit of shopping, '''tea''' and theatres.}}\n# {{lb|en||Southern US}} Specifically [[sweet tea]], an iced tea supersaturated with sugar.\n# {{senseid|en|beverage similar to Camellia sinensis beverage in some way}} Any [[drink]] which is similar to {{taxfmt|Camellia sinensis|species}} tea in some way:\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=2019-02-12|author=Maryea Flaherty|title=Anti-Inflammatory Drinks for Health: 100 Smoothies, Shots, Teas, Broths, and Seltzers to Help Prevent Disease, Lose Weight, Increase Energy, Look Radiant, Reduce Pain, and More!|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9781507209592|page=141\n|text=Mushroom '''Tea''' / 8 cups water / 1 cup dried reishi mushroom pieces [...] 1. Start by making Reishi Mushroom '''Tea''': Bring water to a boil in a medium saucepan. 2. Add the reishi mushroom pieces{{nb...}}}}\n## {{senseid|en|beverage similar to Camellia sinensis beverage but made from other plants}} {{lb|en|uncountable}} Any [[similar]] [[drink]] [[made]] by [[infusing]] [[part]]s of [[various]] [[other]] [[plant]]s.\n##: {{hypo|en|herbal tea}}\n##: {{ux|en|camomile '''tea'''; mint '''tea'''}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|date=2017-01-03|author=Gilles Diederichs|title=My Anti-Stress Year: 52 Weeks of Soothing Activities and Wellness Advice|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9781631581205\n|text=Curcuma '''tea''' relieves colds{{...|, cough, arthritis, and toothaches.}} }}\n## {{senseid|en|meat stock as beverage}} {{lb|en|uncountable|in combination}} [[meat|Meat]] [[stock]] [[serve]]d as a [[hot]] [[drink]].\n##: {{ux|en|beef '''tea'''}}\n# {{senseid|en|one serving of any such beverage}} {{lb|en|countable|Commonwealth|Northern US}} A [[cup]] of any of these [[drink]]s, often with [[milk]], [[sugar]], [[lemon]], or [[tapioca]] [[pearl]]s.\n#: {{ux|en|We'd like one '''tea''' and one coffee, please.}}\n# {{lb|en|East Asia|Southern US}} A [[glass]] of these [[drink]]s.\n# {{senseid|en|midafternoon meal}} {{lb|en|uncountable|UK}} A [[light]] [[midafternoon]] [[meal]], [[typically]] but not [[necessarily]] [[including]] tea.\n#: {{ux|en|I won't make it to the breakfast event, but I'll see you at the '''tea'''.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1951|author=C. S. Lewis|title=Prince Caspian: The Return to Narnia\n|passage=But the gorge of the Rush was not at all a nice place for travelling either. I mean, it was not a nice place for people in a hurry. For an afternoon's ramble ending in a picnic '''tea''' it would have been delightful.}}\n#* {{RQ:Fry Liar|page=16|passage='''Tea''' was a very special institution, revolving as it did around the ceremony and worship of [[toast|Toast]]. In a place {{quote-gloss|public schools}} where alcohol, tobacco and drugs were forbidden, it was essential that something should take their place as a powerful and public totem of virility and cool. Toast, for reasons lost in time, was the substance chosen.}}\n# {{senseid|en|evening meal}} {{lb|en|uncountable|Commonwealth|Ireland}} {{syn of|en|supper}}, the main evening meal, whether or not it includes tea.\n#: {{ux|en|The family were sitting round the table, eating their '''tea'''.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2018|author=Ray Wyre; Tim Tate|title=The Murder of Childhood|page=126\n|passage=Jacki set about making the '''tea'''—bacon grills with chips and bread and butter.}}\n# {{senseid|en|break between sessions in cricket sport}} {{lb|en|cricket}} The [[break]] in [[play]] between the [[second session|second]] and [[third session|third]] [[session]]s.\n#: {{ux|en|Australia were 490 for 7 at '''tea''' on the second day.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2009|journal=w:The Guardian|article_series=Notes and queries: Life and style|title= What do cricketers eat at tea? When is it safe to flush on the train? What's a plujit? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2009/jul/29/notes-and-queries-cricketers-teas\n|passage=As recently as the mid-80s the players would be given a bottle of beer at lunchtime at some county grounds, and \"'''tea'''\" still meant a cup of tea into the 90s.}}\n# {{senseid|en|cannabis}} {{lb|en|slang|dated}} {{syn of|en|marijuana}}.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1940|author=w:Raymond Chandler|title=Farewell, My Lovely|page=103|publisher=Penguin|year_published=2010\n|passage=So they were evidence. Evidence of what? That a man occasionally smoked a stick of '''tea''', a man who looked as if any touch of the exotic would appeal to him. On the other hand lots of tough guys smoked marijuana {{...}}.}}\n#* {{RQ:Mezzrow Blues|page=74|passage='''Tea''' puts a musician in a real masterly sphere, and that's why so many jazzmen have used it.}}\n#* '''1947''' March 11, {{w|William Burroughs}}, letter:\n#*: Here in Texas ''possession'' of '''tea''' is a felony calling for 2&nbsp;years.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=w:Anatole Broyard|title=A Portrait of  the Hipster|work=w:Partisan  Review|month=June|year=1948|passage=Jive music and '''tea''' were the two most important components of the  hipster's life.}}\n#* {{RQ:Kerouac On the Road|passage=Seeing that we didn’t know anything about ourselves, he whipped out three sticks of '''tea''' and said to go ahead, supper’d be ready soon.}}\n# {{senseid|en|information, especially gossip}} {{lb|en|slang|especially|gay slang|and|AAVE}} [[information|Information]], [[especially]] [[gossip]].\n#: {{ux|en|[[spill the tea|Spill the '''tea''']] on that drama, hon.}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|year=1992|writer={{w|Lea DeLaria}}|episode=Ms. DeLaria's Dating Tips for Dykes|title=Bulldyke in a China Shop|medium=spoken-word comedy album|passage=Now I've told you that I've taken LSD, and you think I'm gonna leap through a window or something like that. And you know why that is, that's because of Art Linkletter's daughter.... But let me give you the '''tea''' on her, see, she took LSD, realized she was Art Linkletter's daughter, and threw herself out of the window!}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2015|author=Sonya Shuman|title=Doors of the Church Are Open: Smoke & Mirrors by Sonya Shuman\n|passage=\"What's the '''tea''' on you and China? Where she at Alicia? You should know where ya baby at.\"}}\n#* {{quote-web|en |date=2024 July 23 |url=https://www.distractify.com/p/jd-vance-public-venmo |work=Distractify |author=Sara Belcher |title=JD Vance's Public Venmo Will Make You Want to Private Yours\n|passage=For those looking for '''tea''' on someone, one of the first places you should look is their Venmo account. ... Though most people have found out how to make all of their transactions private, preventing snooping eyes from seeing how many times they've gone out for brunch in the last month, JD Vance hasn't seemed to figure that out yet.\n}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* In most places {{m|en|tea}} is assumed to mean ''[[hot]]'' tea, while in the southern United States, it is assumed to mean {{m|en|iced tea}}.\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|plant}} {{l|en|tea plant}}, {{l|en|tea tree}}, {{l|en|tea bush}}\n* {{sense|leaves}} {{l|en|tea leaves}}\n* {{sense|beverage}} ''see'' [[Thesaurus:tea]]\n* {{sense|beverages similar to tea}} {{l|en|herb tea}}, {{l|en|herbal tea}}, {{l|en|infusion}}, {{l|en|tisane}}\n* {{sense|a light meal}} ''see'' {{l|en|afternoon tea}} ''&'' [[Thesaurus:meal]]\n\n=====Hyponyms=====\n* {{sense|beverage}} ''see'' [[Thesaurus:tea]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|antitea|builders' tea|teabacco|teabagger|teabell|teaboard|teaboo|teabowl|teabox|teacart|teacloth|teaette|teahadist|teahead|teaish|tealess|tealight|tealike|tealite|teamaker|teamaking|tearoom|teatard|teatox|Malcolm X tea|tea shrub\n|Abyssinian tea\n|afternoon tea\n|all the tea in China\n|Appalachian tea|body tea|tea yellows|tea-water|tea-wine|tea-wrap\n|Arabian tea|New Zealand tea tree\n|balm tea|hybrid tea rose|marsh Labrador tea\n|bed-tea,bed tea| tadpole tea|thunder tea rice\n|beef tea\n|black tea|severe tea|tea loaf|bloom tea|China tea|cinder tea\n|boba tea\n|bone apple tea\n|Brazilian tea| Algerian tea|arrowroot tea|kudzu tea\n|breakfast tea\n|brick-tea|hybrid tea|tea mangrove|antitea|builders' tea|teabacco|teabagger|teabell|teaboard|teaboo|teabowl|teabox|teacart|teacloth|teaette|teahadist|teahead|teaish|tealess|tealight|tealike|tealite|teamaker|teamaking|tearoom|teatard|teatox\n|Brigham tea| tea clipper|Ceylon tea\n|bubble tea\n|builder's tea|honeybush tea\n|bush tea\n|Bushman's tea\n|butter tea\n|cambric tea\n|camomile tea\n|chai tea|silk-stocking milk tea|tea biscuit\n|chamomile tea\n|cheese tea\n|chocolate tea\n|clock the tea\n|cocoa tea\n|cowboy tea\n|cowslip tea\n|cream tea\n|cup of tea\n|dandelion tea\n|desert tea\n|Devonshire tea\n|English as afternoon tea\n|English breakfast tea\n|evening tea\n|fever tea\n|fish tea\n|flowering tea\n|fruit tea\n|green tea\n|green-tea cake\n|green tea cake\n|gumboot tea\n|gunpowder tea\n|hay tea\n|herbal tea\n|herb tea\n|high tea\n|husband's tea\n|iced tea\n|ice tea\n|Irish breakfast tea\n|jasmine tea\n|Jesuits' tea\n|kitchen tea\n|Labrador tea\n|lemon tea\n|Long Island iced tea\n|low tea\n|malt tea\n|meat tea\n|Mexican tea\n|milk tea\n|mint tea\n|Mixue Ice Cream & Tea\n|Mormon tea\n|morning tea\n|mountain tea\n|New Jersey tea\n|oolong tea\n|Oswego tea\n|Paris tea\n|Paraguay tea\n|pearl tea\n|picky tea\n|pink tea\n|popcorn tea\n|price of tea in China\n|red tea\n|rich tea biscuit\n|rooibos tea\n|root tea\n|Russian tea\n|sage tea\n|shower tea\n|solar tea\n|someone's cup of tea\n|spill the tea\n|squaw tea\n|storm in a tea-kettle\n|sugar honey ice tea\n|sun tea\n|sweet tea\n|tea and medals\n|tea and toaster\n|tea and toast syndrome\n|tea bag\n|tea ball\n|tea board\n|tea boat\n|tea bowl\n|tea bread\n|tea break\n|tea buffet\n|tea caddy\n|tea candle\n|tea card\n|tea cart\n|tea ceremony\n|tea chest\n|tea chest bass\n|tea chest bassist\n|tea clam\n|tea cloth\n|tea cosey\n|tea cosy\n|tea cozy\n|tea cup\n|tea dance\n|tea dress\n|tea egg\n|tea fight\n|tea garden\n|tea gown\n|Tea Green\n|tea house\n|tea jenny\n|tea kettle\n|tea kitchen\n|tea lady\n|tea lead\n|tea leaf\n|tea leaf paradox\n|tea leaves\n|tea light\n|tea maker\n|tea money\n|tea oil\n|tea oil camellia\n|tea oil plant\n|tea olive\n|tea pad\n|tea party\n|tea pet\n|tea plant\n|tea pot\n|tea room\n|tea rose\n|tea sandwich\n|tea service\n|tea set\n|tea shades\n|tea shop\n|tea stick\n|tea strainer\n|tea table\n|tea towel\n|tea tray\n|tea tree oil\n|tea trolley\n|tea urn\n|tea wagon\n|tea whisk\n|tea-and-toaster\n|tea-bag\n|tea-board\n|tea-caddy\n|tea-cake\n|tea-cosy\n|tea-cup\n|tea-dress\n|tea-gown\n|tea-gowned\n|tea-kettle\n|tea-leaf\n|tea-length\n|tea-light\n|tea-pot\n|tea-poy\n|tea-leafing\n|tea-leaved\n|tea-leaved willow\n|tea-service\n|tea-set\n|tea-table\n|tea-things\n|tea-time\n|tea-towel\n|tea-tray\n|tea-urn\n|tea-whisk\n|teabag\n|teaberry\n|teaboy\n|teacake\n|teacup\n|teaghrelin\n|teahouse\n|teakettle\n|teamster tea\n|teapot\n|teaspoon\n|teatime\n|teaware\n|tempest in a tea-kettle\n|Texas tea\n|theezan tea\n|thick tea\n|vampire tea bag\n|weak tea\n|West India tea\n|what does that have to do with the price of tea in China\n|white tea\n|without tea and biscuits\n|worm tea\n|yellow tea\n}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n{{top2}}\n* {{desc|gul|tea}}\n* {{desc|jam|tea}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|abe|ti}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|cic|tii'}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|coc|ṭi·}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|kw|té}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|cr|-}}\n*: {{desc|sclang=1|cr|ᑎᕀ}}\n*: {{desc|sclang=1|cr|tiy}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|iu|ᑏ}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|ga|tae}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|mi|tī}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|pqm|ti}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|mik|ti'g'tlo'q|ji'gitlo'q|t2=kettle}} {{q|from \"tea kettle\"}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|par|tii}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|gd|tì|teatha}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|ta|டீ}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|shi|atay}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|te|టీ}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|unm|ti}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|cy|te}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{see translation subpage|Noun}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb|+|+|+,~'d,~d}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[drink]] tea.\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|editor=w:William Shawcross|chapter=Elizabeth|title=Counting One’s Blessings: The Selected Letters of Queen Elizabeth the Queen Mother|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Farrar, Straus and Giroux|date=28 March 1916|year_published=2012|page=32|passage=We '''tea’d''' with May, and had to wait over an hour for a taxi!}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Benjamin Disraeli|title=Benjamin Disraeli Letters: 1835-1837|location=Toronto; Buffalo; London|publisher=w:University of Toronto Press|year=1837|year_published=1982|page=319|isbn=0-8020-5587-7|passage=I dined yesterday at {{!}} three on mutton chops and 1/2 pint of E[ast] I [ndian] sherry, and then '''''tead''''' and muffined' at 8.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=Desmos of Delta Sigma Delta|year=1921|page=41|passage=We coffeed and '''tead''' and smoked a trench torch with Grand Master Browning, and cranked our Cadillac for another station.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To take [[afternoon tea]] {{gl|a light meal}}.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1877|title=The Bicycling Times and Tourist's Gazette|page=38\n|passage=The wind was high and the hills ditto, and both being against us we were late in reaching Hitchin (30 from Cambridge), so giving up the idea of reaching Oxford we toiled on through Luton, on to Dunstable (47), where we '''teaed''' moderately {{...}}}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give tea to.\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Benedict Cruiser|editor=w:George Augustus Sala|chapter=Of the Agonising Process by which that which was once a Bower of Bliss was converted into a Cave of Despair|title=How I Tamed Mrs. Cruiser|location=London|publisher=James Blackwood|year=1858|page=129|passage=And they’ve got Professor Hummums with ’em, the great Everlasting Star of the Nineteenth Century, which he has breakfasted and dined and '''tea’d''' and supped here ever since yesterday.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|chapter=I|title=Hospital Transports. A Memoir of the Embarkation of the Sick and Wounded from the Peninsula of Virginia in the Summer of 1862.|location=Boston, Mass.|publisher=w:Ticknor and Fields|year=1863|page=25|passage=In half an hour they had all been '''tea’d''' and coffeed and refreshed by the nurses, and shortly after were all undressed and put to bed clean and comfortable, and in a droll state of grateful wonder;}}\n#* {{RQ:Worboise St Beetha's|chapter=The St. Beetha's Temperance Society|page=213|passage=But one or two evil-disposed characters muttered they might be sure the lady had her own turn to serve, and they might be sure they wasn't \"'''teaed''' and muffined and sandwiched for nothing!\"}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=The Public|year=1909|page=109|passage=This gentleman was presented by Colonel C. E. S. Wood, and was entertained here—wined, dined, '''tead''', breakfasted, coffeed and luncheoned—and we bought his pictures.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Jordaina Sydney Robinson|title=Dead Completely|series=Afterlife Adventures Series|year=2019|passage=After I’d '''tea’d''' everyone and Oz had breakfasted them,{{...}}}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{en-adj}}\n\n# {{rfv-sense|en}} {{lb|en|slang}} [[good-looking|Good-looking]], [[sexy]].\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{sl|en|zh|茶|t=tea}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A [[moment]], a historical unit of time from China, about the amount of time needed to quickly drink a traditional cup of tea.\n\n=====Usage notes=====\nThis term is found in English translations of Chinese-language historical fiction, where it is used to give the work an ancient Chinese feel.\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=aet|eta|æt.|-ate|eat|AET|aet|a.e.t.|ETA|aet.|ate|Até|eta.|Atë}}\n\n{{C|en|Ericales order plants|Marijuana|Meals|Tea|Time|Units of measure}}\n\n==Asturian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{uder|ast|la|taeda}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{ast-noun|f|tees}}\n\n# [[torch]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{nonlemma}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|ast|verb form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|ast|tar||1//3|s|pres|subj}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:ast:DALLA}}\n* {{R:ast:DGLA|id=70664}}\n\n==Basque==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|eu|noun form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|eu|te||absv|s}}\n\n==Chinese==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{bor|yue|en|tea}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{zh-pron\n|c=ti1\n|cat=n\n}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|zh|noun}}\n\n# {{lb|zh|Hong Kong Cantonese}} [[afternoon tea]] {{zh-mw|c:個}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col3|yue|食tea|high tea}}\n\n==Ese==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|mcq|noun}}\n\n# [[feces]]; [[excrement]]\n\n==Estonian==\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|et|verb form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|et|teadma||pres|indc|connegative}}\n# {{inflection of|et|teadma||2|s|impr}}\n\n==Galician==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|gl|roa-opt|tea}} (13th century, {{w|Cantigas de Santa Maria}}), from {{inh|gl|la|tēla}}. Cognate with {{cog|pt|teia}} and {{cog|es|tela}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|gl|/ˈtea̝/}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{gl-noun|f}}\n\n# {{lb|gl|uncountable}} [[cloth]]\n# {{lb|gl|countable}} a piece of [[cloth]]\n#* {{quote-book|gl|year=1326|editor=Antonio López Ferreiro|title=Galicia Histórica. Colección diplomática|location=Santiago|publisher=Tipografía Galaica|page=300\n|passage=''It. mando que todollos lenços delgados et '''teas''' de rens que os tome Garcia perez. et que faça delles fazer uestimentas para o altar de Sta Maria.''\n|translation=Item, I command that every fine linen and the '''clothes''' of Reims to be taken by Garcia Perez, who should make them into clothes for the altar of Saint Mary}}\n# [[spiderweb]]\n#: {{syn|gl|arañeira}}\n# [[canvas]]\n#: {{syn|gl|lenzo}}\n# [[film]] {{gl|skin}}\n#: {{syn|gl|película}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|gl|tear}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|gl|roa-opt|tea}} (13th century, {{w|Cantigas de Santa Maria}}), from {{inh|gl|la|taeda}}, from {{der|gl|grc|δάος||torch}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|gl|/ˈtea̝/}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{gl-noun|f}}\n\n# [[torch]]\n#: {{syn|gl|facha|fachuzo}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:gl:DDGM}}\n* “[http://sli.uvigo.es/xelmirez/xelmirez.php?pescuda=+tea&corpus=xelmirez tea]” in Xavier Varela Barreiro & Xavier Gómez Guinovart: Corpus Xelmírez - Corpus lingüístico da Galicia medieval. SLI / Grupo TALG / ILG, 2006-2016.\n* {{R:gl:DDLG}}\n* {{R:gl:TILG}}\n* {{R:TLPGP}}\n\n==Hungarian==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{bor|hu|nl|thee}}, from {{der|hu|nan-hbl|茶|tr=tê||tea}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{hu-IPA|tea|teja}}\n* {{hyphenation|hu|tea}}\n* {{rhymes|hu|ɒ|jɒ|s=2}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{hu-noun|~|pl=teák}}\n\n# {{l|en|tea}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{hu-infl-nom|teá|o}}{{hu-pos-tok|teá}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|hu\n|gyógytea\n|teás\n|teázik\n}}\n{{col4|hu|title=Compound words\n|csalántea\n|csipkebogyótea\n|gyümölcstea\n|hársfatea\n|kamillatea\n|teacserje\n|teadélután\n|teafilter\n|teafőző\n|teaház\n|teakeverék\n|teakonyha\n|tealevél\n|teamécses\n|tearózsa\n|teasütemény\n|teaszűrő\n|teaültetvény\n|teavaj\n|zsurlótea\n}}\n{{col4|hu|title=Expressions\n|fekete tea\n|zöld tea\n}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|rsk|тея|bor=1}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:ErtSz}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|hu|Eta}}<!-- feminine given name -->\n\n{{cln|hu|3-letter words}}\n{{topics|hu|Beverages|Tea}}\n\n==Māori==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|mi|poz-pol-pro|*tea}}. Compare {{cog|haw|kea}} and {{cog|rap|tea tea}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{mi-IPA|tea|stress='-}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{mi-adj}}\n\n# [[white]]\n#: {{syn|mi|mā}}\n# light-coloured\n# [[clear]], [[transparent]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|mi|Aotearoa}}\n* {{l|mi|Ao-tea-roa}}\n\n{{table:colors/mi}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ang-IPA|tēa}}\n* {{rhymes|ang|æ͜ɑː|s=1}}\n\n===Numeral===\n{{head|ang|numeral|head=tēa}}\n\n# {{lb|ang|Northumbrian}} {{alternative form of|ang|tīen}}\n\n==Rapa Nui==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|mi|poz-pol-pro|*tea}}. Compare {{cog|haw|kea}} and {{cog|mi|tea}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|rap|noun}}\n\n# [[dawn]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|rap|tea tea}}\n\n==Sedang==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|sed|noun}}\n\n# [[water]]\n# [[body]] of [[water]]: [[river]], [[lake]], etc\n# [[liquid]]\n# [[wine]]\n\n===References===\n* Kenneth D. Smith, ''[http://www.sil.org/silepubs/Pubs/928474543107/LCDD_17_Sedang_dictionary.pdf Sedang Dictionary]'' (2012), page 375\n\n==Spanish==\n{{was fwotd|es|2022|March|27}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|es|teda||rare}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|es|la|tēda}}, early [[monophthongize]]d variant of {{der|es|la|taeda||torch}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{es-pr}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{es-noun|f}}\n\n# [[torch]] {{gl|a stick with a flame on one end, used chiefly as a light source}}\n#: {{syn|es|antorcha}}\n#* {{quote-book|es\n|title=s:es:La conquista del reino de Maya por el último conquistador español Pío Cid|author=w:Ángel Ganivet|year=1897|page=[[s:es:La conquista del reino de Maya por el último conquistador español Pío Cid: 05|5]]|passage=La reunión terminaba siempre cuando se iban a apagar las '''teas''', cuya duración era de cuatro o cinco horas.\n|translation=The meeting ended whenever the '''torches''', whose duration was about four or five hours, were going to go out.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|es\n|title=El Viaje del Lector: Alemania|author=Gertrudis María Glück|date=August 18 2013|journal=Clarín|passage=En esa época en que aún no existía el vidrio, para resguardarse del frío se tapiaban las ventanas con tablas de madera. A su vez, la iluminación se realizaba con '''teas''' que llenaban de humo los ambientes cerrados.\n|translation=In that era when glass still didn't exist, to protect themselves from the cold, they boarded up windows with wooden planks. In turn, lighting was achieved with '''torches''' that filled closed environments with smoke.\n|url=https://www.clarin.com/viajes/Alemania_0_ryWfnMroPme.html}}\n# {{lb|es|colloquial}} [[intoxication]], [[drunkenness]]\n#: {{syn|es|Thesaurus:borrachera}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:es:DRAE}}"}}